title: Anycubic i3 Mega Custom hotend cover + 2x fan duct + laser mount holes

description.text:
About

This thing is designed to replace the original metal cover and fan duct of Anycubic i3 Mega 3D printer.

Updates

  • 06.11.17 - Initial upload
  • 10.11.17 - Added the version with no cover. You should use it with the original metal covering. Some holes were enlarged a little for easier mounting. All files reuploaded.

Main features:

  1. No metal drilling or even additional screws are needed to assemble. Never the less, using thread tap is recommended since the holes are a little tight.
  2. The holes in front of every cooler are completely removed. This solution increases the airflow and removes that annoying "whistling" sound.
  3. The air is blown though the gap form inside of the torus. The air-blowing gap has a round shape and has different size according to the distance form the fan.
  4. The airflow form the hotend-fan is guided directly on hotend and thus is used more efficiently.
  5. The laser mount holes are designed to suite this cheap chinese laser heatsink. No need to mount/dismount laser for every engraving operation because it suites perfectly and doesn't collide with the metal frame of the printer within the whole range of X axis.

Printer:

Anycubic i3 Mega

Doesn't Matter

Yes

55%

Notes:

Support type:

The support is necessary to print outer cover and the gap inside the torus. It is recommended to create custom support (if using Simplify3D) or to use support on build plate only in other slicers. Otherwise, if creating full automatic support, you will be unable to remove the support from inside of the torus.

Print material:

Use ABS or other heat-resistant filament. Otherwise printed part may deform in some time during usage.

title: Amiibo Stand System - With Connectors
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Edit 12/3/2017: I finally printed a full 3x4 Amiibo stand with connectors! I've uploaded the final print and made it the cover. Yay!

Amiibo were taking over the house, so I decided to do something about it!

First, I made a beautiful stand:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2613221

Which was based on a fantastic guide:

https://imgur.com/gallery/P68cT

I went to print it out, and it was hilariously larger than the maximum size of my FFCP 2016.

So then, I did what any engineer would do: I sketched out a modular system!

Originally, as a test, I made a no-connector (connectorless?) system, that you could use to make your own base, using glue or tape to stick things together:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2625743

That was cool, and it allowed me to test the blocks/modules to make sure they'd print right, look good, and hold Amiibo properly. I'm sure some folks will be happy with the connector-free modules, and will simply use super glue or tape to hold things together.

Me, I knew I wanted something with connectors. I like curves, but I realized that circles are fully symmetrical, and would allow rotation. These should go together perfectly at right angles, 180°, so I decided on a two-way keying system (because one-way is annoying) in the oval. You can connect these right-side-up or upside-down, but that's about it. If you wanted something a little more fool-proof, I could probably do a system that had a softened (curved point) triangle, which would allow for only one real way (the other ways would not be at 90° angles). I could even put in an asymmetrical hole but, honestly, that's just getting too confusing. Plus, these modules are symmetrical, so you can rotate them, and use them however.

There are six different types of modules, in three different heights.

The types of modules are: no holes, one hole, two corner holes, two opposite holes, three holes and four holes. Obviously, the "no holes" won't connect to anything unless you're willing to use glue, tape, or for something stand-alone. I promise I won't judge you! Obviously, the other five modules are for connecting with the provided "rods." The "tight rod" feels like a porn star name. It's not. Printed at Medium (0.2mm) layer height, it's a snug fit. You may have to clean up the end(s) a little bit, but in mine, I just had to give a little pressure and the rod slid into the hole no problem. If one side is tighter, press that side in manually first, and then slide the other module into the looser rod end. That should make things easier.

I was playing with a "max" sized height (maximum Z height of the FFCP 2016 edition), but realized most folks are going to want to start out with the low, medium and high designed here. I used the Fibonacci sequence (Golden Ratio), to design the heights, widths and lengths. I enjoy good design, and hope you find these visually appealing.

I will share my sketch later, so you can see how I originally intended for this to be used. It's a free-form sketch, so don't judge me or my artistic ability!

If you make one of these, please share a Make here. I love to see what people do with my Things. Seriously!

If you have a suggestion, comment or question, please leave a comment somewhere on this Thing. I try to take suggestions and make them a reality. One of the ideas I had originally was to make a two-by on the top, so you could have a larger margin/area to display some of the "fatter" Amiibo, while still looking good. I may share/print the "max" size items, but we'll see how I feel. I think the three-tier system works fairly well, but at some point, when you get out to eight or nine wide, a fourth layer might make it look better than just the three. We'll see.

Notes:

I tried to print this with sub-30% infill and the outcome was terrible. That's not to say it wasn't my filament, leveling, or type of support structure that was to blame. But I think 30% gives you a nice solid "feel" without spending too much time and filament printing. Even the connecting rods printed nicely at 30%. I didn't feel like anything was going to break. Basically, your mileage may vary at lower infill percentages. But have fun!

Easy Cleanup

Very little clean-up is required for these. Depending on your slicer and printer tolerances, you may end up with support material inside the connector holes. I enabled support, and it didn't fill the holes on the two test modules shown with the three loose connectors.

There are two different rods: tight (for friction) and glue (if you want to glue). I haven't tested the glue size yet, but I removed 0.2mm off of the top and side of the rod's ellipse, so that should give you enough space for gluing. I will probably test the "glue rod" soon.

Fusion 360 and Simplify3D

I love Fusion 360. It "just works" and although they are always improving it, it does everything I need it to do right now. It lets me explore the world of 3D with less stress, because parametric design is the way to make things properly. A lot of folks are into "organic" design, and that's just not me. I like angles, and curves, and I like to see things unfold mathematically in front of my eyes. And if I don't like something, I can change a number or two here and there, and make things just the way I like them. Parametric design makes it so that if I want to go back later, and change the size of these modules, I can just change two or three numbers in one place, and all the modules just snap to the right size. It's pretty awesome.

Simplify3D is my choice of slicer. It just works. It knows my printer, and I rarely have any issues with it. I know that over time they will add additional features and improvements, but just like Fusion 360, it does everything I need it to do, and then some.

I transmit the output files to my Toshiba FlashAir SD card in my FlashForge Creator Pro (2016) printer, and monitor my prints remotely (upstairs) using a Raspberry Pi and camera module.

description.text:
A simple filament detector that pauses the printer and waits patiently to be fed more filament.

The instructions I've provided are for a Duet-powered Tevo Little Monster. Perhaps someone can comment on how to work with the stock Smoothie. Here's a head start: http://smoothieware.org/switch#pause-when-out-of-filament

Tevo LM Filament Guide v4 - Detector.stl - Trimmed .5mm off the diameter and fillet the front so it should be easier to snap into place but still be fairly snug. Thanks, AK_Eric.

Printer:

Tevo Little Monster

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

I use 3D Solutech Teal Blue PLA.

Bill of Materials

Obtain the following materials:

  • (1) print the part, obviously
  • (1) SPDT roller rocker switch (http://amzn.to/2AnCN2c)
  • (1) piece of 2 conductor wire long enough to reach the switch and mainboard
  • (1) 3pin Molex KK plug w/ (2) ferrules (should have an extra leftover in your Duet kit)
  • (2) M2x20 bolts w/ nuts (M2.5 are shown, it's all I had and I had to drill out the holes in the switch to accommodate)
  • (2) M3x6 bolts
Makeup the plug

Fortunately, the polarity isn't an issue so solder/connect the 2 conductors on one end of the wire to the Normally Closed (NC) leads of the rocker switch. Use some heat shrink or electrical tape to protect the leads. On the other end, connect the ferrules and insert into pin 1 & 3 slots on the plug.

Install switch to grommet

Slide the switch into the bracket with the roller facing down (towards the grommet). Fasten the switch using the bolts and loosely tighten the nuts for adjustment.

Tip: you may want to put a drop of sewing machine oil on the roller because it will start to squeak over time. #experience Adjust the position of the switch

Using a piece of filament, position the switch till you hear a click or use a multimeter to test continuity. I found tilting the switch back slightly offered maximum actuation while still making it easy to thread the filament through.

Install the bracket

Push the bracket through the underside of the top plate. Align the holes of the bracket to the preexisting holes of the bracket. Use the M3 bolts to fasten the bracket to the top plate.

Tip: use an Allen wrench to help guide the bracket into place since it's a tight fit. Plug into the mainboard

With the printer off, plug the Molex KK into the E1 Stop jack.

Configure the sensor

Add the following to config.g file anywhere before the M501 command:
; Filament Sensor
M591 D0 P1 C4 R20 ; configure extruder drive 0 to use E1 endstop (C4) with 20% tolerance
M591 D0 ; display filament sensor parameters for extruder drive 0

If all is working you should receive the following popup on DWC with the print paused.

description.text:
Compact housing for HEPA "aer" filters that uses 60mm fan. Seals tightly, works well, real-world tested.

The back is flat with 3x M5 holes to secure directly to an enclosure wall.

Instructions: Print 5 parts. Print them with the joining edges on the bed as this will give you the flattest/most true surface when you try to stick them together.

I printed in ABS and used acetone to join them together.
Don't use PETG as you won't be able to join them with sufficient strength.
Other materials...just make sure you can join them together somehow.

Use a fan with decent static pressure ratings so it can pull the air through, but not too high of a flow rate as to create big drafts in your enclosure. I found the Noctua 60mm fan worked very well: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B009NQMESS/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Background: I wasn't very convinced the Roomba "hepa" filters on Amazon were actually very HEPA. The "aer" filters are not cheap, but they are compact and 1) are sold by a 1st party vendor, 2) are represented to be HEPA and 3) actually look like they could be HEPA. Remember, if the filter isn't actually HEPA you are just exposing yourself to dangerous UFP's.
If you use ABS, use acetone and "acid brush" to join/melt the 5 pieces together. Does not require clamping, but you must hold them together for about a minute each.

title: Anet A8 Titan Aero carriage & fan duct

description.text:
I remixed this great extruder carriage from ade2 to fit my Anet A8. I really like the way you can see the nozzle without lots of stuff in the way. The sensor is also nice and close to the nozzle and you can get access to the hobbed gear easily if it gets clogged or flexible filament gets kinked

I did make some tweaks to the design. I changed the rods of the X axis so they are the distance apart as the stock Anet A8 X axis. I am using a Chinese clone of the E3D Titan Aero extruder which had a slightly larger pancake stepper motor than the e3d one.

I wasnt a fan of the way the sensor was fixed to the main body with zip ties. I think that the induction sensor and the nozzle should be as rigid as possible. So I used screws. What I am a big fan of however is threaded brass inserts which I used four M3x4x4 variaty (which you can get 50 for £2). You use a soldering iron to heat up the insert and when hot it will easily melt into the hole leaving a threaded hole that will be strong and will not wear out easily, like if you thread directly into the ABS Plastic. (I did also included a stl of the carriage which doesn't use threaded inserts and instead has the holes sized correctly in the print for screwing M3 screws directly into the plastic, if you don't like the idea of buying inserts.

The downside of this design is that you loose 15mm from your Y axis. Unless of course you create a new Y axis mount

El “Euphoria” es un avión realmente polivalente, si lo acompañas con un motor suave es muy fácil de llevar y si por el contrario lo equipas con algo potente se vuelve muy rápido y divertido. Yo te recomiendo que lo pruebes con una potencia de 1400kv y una hélice 8×4 que te de un consumo de unos 22A. Una vez lo tengas trimado puedes ponerle algo más potente como un 2200kv y una hélice de 6×4 con un consumo de 30A. La batería a utilizar puede ser desde una 2200 2s hasta una 1600 3s o una 2200 3s, lo que creas conveniente procurando no excederte de un peso de 250 gramos.Su polivalencia no acaba ahí y como muestra de ello te propongo dos configuraciones diferentes para que te diviertas aún más con esta máquina de volar. title: Dehydrator Panels
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
These panels are designed for a ~150mm diameter dehydrator. 4 of these make a complete circle and enclose the dehydrator with the cap on top. They are used to dry filaments and desiccants. The panels are 15mm high and can hold at least two 1kg spools, leaving ample space for other things. These panels are vertically stackable as well to add more filament spools.

Included SolidWorks file for easy modifications. If you are in the market for a dehydrator, I'd recommend one with circular shape rather than an elliptical shape. Ellipse make things a bit more complicated. Also, you can get a used one for quite cheap. I got mine (in the picture) for only $20.

Update: I ended up using a diaper box (very strong corrugated cardboard) and some duct tape (see pictures above). It can dry 8 spools and a whole host of things at the same time.

title: Pre-Filter Cover for Bosch Pro GAS 12V Vac

description.text:
This is a self-made cover for the paper-filter of the Bosch Professional 12V (== 10.8V) accu vacuum cleaner.

It protects the original filter against damage from little stones etc.

As there is some space left between the top of the paper filter and the top mesh of this cover, you can also add some filter fibre to build a prefilter. This way, the fine and hard to clean lamellas of the original Bosch filter don't fill up with dirt and dust so fast.

Until now, I followed a quite known hint from the internet to build a prefilter by modding some Dirt Devil filter, but now I created this part, which (as opposed to the Dirt Devil based solution) fits just perfectly onto the Bosch filter

Still have some ideas for a version 2.0, but this version already fits and works very well. if you also have some ideas, just add a comment. I may consider it for a future release.

Notes:

Be sure to have a well-leveled print bed because of the relatively fine mesh structure.

I used Simplify 3D to setup special print settings für the first 3mm (slower, setup to print the fine details of the mesh), and some faster settings for the rest of the part, and it came out just perfectly nice.

Supports shouldn't be needed, as all overhangs have an angle of <= 40 degrees.

I used 0,2mm layer height printed with an 0,4mm nozzle.

title: Calibration tool with Z axis test

description.text:
This calibration tool has a 20mm square base and has steps of 10mm intervals up to a height of 40mm.

This tool let's you test the accuracy of all three axis but unlike a simple 20mm cube if you have an issue with the Z axis you can test whether it is due to errors in the Z step value or whether it is a z offset issue. You can see in my case that I have a consist .3 reduction in height regardless of where measured so in this instance it is a z offset/start issue (probably).

If it's a z step issue the error will increase the higher up you take the measurement.

In my photos I'm using a cheap vernier from amazon approx $10 and only has a resolution down to 0.1 mm but for most things this is adequate
